description: From un- (“lack or absence of”) +‎ will (noun).

entries.meaning: Lack or absence of will; willlessness; undesire.
examples: The first challenge to shaping and taming this emerging world is the will itself and the human problem of unwill, especially in relation to femininity.

verbs.description: unwill (third-person singular simple present unwills, present participle unwilling, simple past and past participle unwilled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To annul or reverse by an act of the will.
